  <title>OCCI Infrastructure</title>

  <para>OCCI Infrastructure defines three kinds and various extensions
  relating to management of cloud infrastructure services (IaaS).</para>

  <table>
    <title>Common Attributes</title>

    <tgroup cols="3">
      <colspec align="center" />

      <thead>
        <row>
          <entry align="left">Attribute</entry>

          <entry>Type</entry>

          <entry>Description</entry>
        </row>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <row>
          <entry
          align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Infrastructure-Hostname</computeroutput></entry>

          <entry>String</entry>

          <entry>Valid DNS hostname for the resource (may be FQDN)</entry>
        </row>
      </tbody>
    </tgroup>
  </table>

  <section>
    <title>Kinds</title>

    <para>Cloud infrastructure can be modeled using three primary kinds:
    <computeroutput>compute</computeroutput>,
    <computeroutput>network</computeroutput> and
    <computeroutput>storage</computeroutput>.</para>

    <table>
      <title>Kinds</title>

      <tgroup cols="3">
        <colspec align="center" />

        <thead>
          <row>
            <entry align="left">Kind</entry>

            <entry>URI</entry>

            <entry>Description</entry>
          </row>
        </thead>

        <tbody>
          <row>
            <entry
            align="left"><computeroutput>compute</computeroutput></entry>

            <entry><uri>http://purl.org/occi/kind/compute</uri></entry>

            <entry>Information processing resources</entry>
          </row>

          <row>
            <entry
            align="left"><computeroutput>network</computeroutput></entry>

            <entry><uri>http://purl.org/occi/kind/network</uri></entry>

            <entry>Interconnection resources</entry>
          </row>

          <row>
            <entry
            align="left"><computeroutput>storage</computeroutput></entry>

            <entry><uri>http://purl.org/occi/kind/storage</uri></entry>

            <entry>Recorded information resources</entry>
          </row>
        </tbody>
      </tgroup>
    </table>

    <section>
      <title>Compute</title>

      <para>A compute resource is capable of conducting computations (e.g. a
      virtual machine).</para>

      <table>
        <title>Compute Attributes</title>

        <tgroup cols="3">
          <colspec align="center" />

          <thead>
            <row>
              <entry align="left">Attribute</entry>

              <entry>Type</entry>

              <entry>Description</entry>
            </row>
          </thead>

          <tbody>
            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Compute-CPU-Arch</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Enum (x86, x64)</entry>

              <entry>CPU Architecture (e.g. x64)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Compute-CPU-Cores</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Integer</entry>

              <entry>Number of CPU cores (e.g. 1, 2)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Compute-CPU-Speed</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Float (10^9 Hertz)</entry>

              <entry>Clock speed in gigahertz (e.g. 2.4)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Compute-Memory-Size</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Float (10^6 bytes)</entry>

              <entry>RAM in megabytes (e.g. 2048)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Compute-Memory-Speed</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Float (10^9 bps)</entry>

              <entry>RAM speed in Gbit/s (e.g. 256)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Compute-Memory-Reliability</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Enum (standard, checksum)</entry>

              <entry>Qualitative measure of RAM reliability (e.g. ECC)</entry>
            </row>
          </tbody>
        </tgroup>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title>Network</title>

      <para>A network resource is capable of transferring data (e.g. a virtual
      network or VLAN).</para>

      <table>
        <title>Network Attributes</title>

        <tgroup cols="3">
          <colspec align="center" />

          <thead>
            <row>
              <entry align="left">Attribute</entry>

              <entry>Type</entry>

              <entry>Description</entry>
            </row>
          </thead>

          <tbody>
            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Network-VLAN-Id</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Integer (0..4095)</entry>

              <entry>802.1q VLAN ID (e.g. 4095)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Network-VLAN-Tag</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Token</entry>

              <entry>Tag based VLANs (e.g. external-dmz)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Network-IPv4-n-Address</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>IPv4 Address</entry>

              <entry>IPv4 gateway address (e.g. 192.168.0.1)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Network-IPv4-n-Netmask</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>IPv4 Address</entry>

              <entry>IPv4 netmask address (e.g. 255.255.255.0)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Network-IPv4-n-Network</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>IPv4 Address</entry>

              <entry>IPv4 network address (e.g. 192.168.0.0)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Network-IPv4-n-CIDR</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Integer (0..32)</entry>

              <entry>Netmask in CIDR notation (e.g. 24)</entry>
            </row>
          </tbody>
        </tgroup>
      </table>

      <remark>TODO: Tidy up network interface addressing.</remark>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title>Storage</title>

      <para>A storage resource is capable of mass storage of data (e.g. a
      virtual hard drive).</para>

      <table>
        <title>Storage Attributes</title>

        <tgroup cols="3">
          <colspec align="center" />

          <thead>
            <row>
              <entry align="left">Attribute</entry>

              <entry>Type</entry>

              <entry>Description</entry>
            </row>
          </thead>

          <tbody>
            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Storage-Reliability</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Enum (transient, persistent, reliable)</entry>

              <entry>Qualitative device persistence (e.g. transient)</entry>
            </row>

            <row>
              <entry
              align="left"><computeroutput>OCCI-Storage-Size</computeroutput></entry>

              <entry>Integer (10^9 bytes)</entry>

              <entry>Drive size in gigabytes (e.g. 40)</entry>
            </row>
          </tbody>
        </tgroup>
      </table>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Extensions</title>

    <para>Various extensions provide for more advanced management
    functionality such as billing, monitoring and reporting.</para>

    <section>
      <title>State machine (state)</title>

      <para>The state machine extension allows for the modeling of arbitrarily
      complex state machines and associated transitions (e.g. start, stop,
      restart).</para>
    </section>
  </section>
</article>
